                <a href="https://www.oyez.org/cases/2016/16-405"><i>BNSF Railway Co. v. Tyrrell</i></a> (5/30/17)
                <br/> The Montana Supreme Court erred in holding that 45 U.S.C. 56 grants state courts personal jurisdiction over a railroad company that merely “does business” in and is “found within” that state. For a state court to exercise general jurisdiction over an out-of-state corporation, the corporation must have such “continuous and systematic” ties to the state as to render it essentially at home in that state. Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg delivered the opinion for the 8-1 majority, with Justice Sonia Sotomayor writing separately to concur in part and dissent in part.
