                <a href="https://www.oyez.org/cases/2016/15-1189"><i>Impression Products, Inc. v. Lexmark International, Inc.</i></a> (5/30/17)
                <br/> Selling a patented product exhausts all of the patent holder’s rights in the product, whether or not it imposes any restrictions on the purchaser, since the restrictions may be enforced only through contract law rather than a patent infringement claim. Thus Lexmark’s selling of its patented product exhausted its patent rights in the ink cartridges, so any attempt to enforce restrictions on the use of the product by the purchaser must be done as a matter of contract law, not through a patent infringement lawsuit. Chief Justice John Roberts delivered the 7-1 majority opinion, with Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg writing separately to concur in part and dissent in part.
            </p>
